english:
  title: A Memorial Expressing Gratitude for the Imperial Rescript in Two Sealed Caskets
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly addresses the throne:

    Your servant's late elder brother, the former King, previously dispatched his attendant, the provisional inspector of the imperial guard Kim Gyun and others, bearing memorials to congratulate the late emperor upon his return from the western campaign and the restoration of the imperial carriage to the palace. In addition, he submitted a separate memorial celebrating the execution of the rebel Huang Chao. Now, through Your Majesty's gracious beneficence, two sealed caskets containing imperial rescripts have been bestowed, along with special tokens of favor. From the heights where the celestial wheel turns, the phoenix-adorned rescripts have descended, spreading their brilliance to illuminate the distant borderlands and stirring the deep sorrow of our ancestral tombs. For this, your servant offers heartfelt gratitude.

    Your servant, as king of his domain, reflects upon the ancient times when Zhou and Qin alternated and the kingdoms of Yan and Zhao knew great turmoil. Just as fair maidens drew pearls from their native waters and worthy warriors transformed through enlightenment, our ancestors came to establish this realm and defend the remote corners of the tributary lands. Thus Jinhan acquired its name, and Lelang took its characters, though we inherited the residual disorders of the burning of books and followed those who fled calamity. Striving to model ourselves upon antiquity, we long remained ignorant of the arts of transforming customs and manners. Like those with hair held between their teeth, who might transmit the brush strokes of five colors to us?

    With the Guoyu and Xiaojing, it was exceedingly difficult to transform our customs; with the Book of Changes kept at the bedside, few could even name it truly. Yet your servant's late elder brother, the Grand Tutor, was one who understood the teachings of the ancients from birth and spoke the language of the old masters with excellence. His talents were not merely distinguished—they were resplendent—and his discourse was abundant and flowing. Thus his person illuminated the world with refinement, and his calligraphy transcended the common. Ever ashamed of remaining a mere official beyond the screen, he longed only to follow the immortals in the jar. His aspirations found expression in verse and song, sources of profound lamentation.

    When news came that the late emperor had halted his hunting expedition in the Brocade River and was returning to the Crimson Palace, and that the rulers of the eastern domains had united to drive away the tigers and leopards and display the slain whales and rays, your servant's joy knew no bounds. With heart overflowing, he personally composed a memorial and uttered words of praise. Though his composition might flow somewhat differently from those of the western regions, yet it should reach the great sea; and though he could not claim all the beauty of the southeast, yet he dared hope it might move heaven.

    Your servant has now humbly received the imperial rescripts, sent forth from the throne, transcending all ordinary protocols. The pair of phoenix-emblazoned caskets point the way to the Mountain of Immortals, while the dragon-adorned scroll enters our humble land beyond the eastern seas. This is truly a pearl of incalculable worth descended from heaven, and our entire nation has become a grass that shall never wither. Examining the words of the rescript, it commands: "Fix your heart ever more firmly, never forget your allegiance to righteousness, diligently cultivate the rituals of proper authority, harmonize with the ways of civilization, that the bright merit may be foremost among all lands and the flowing grace perpetually nourish your realm."

    Your servant recalls that the ancients, such as Di Wu Lun, would weep upon reading the imperial rescripts of Han Guangwu, saying to his peers: "This is truly a sage ruler! How I regret not being able to meet him!" Now, having received the rescripts of our enlightened sovereign, your servant feels as though hearing the words of a loving father. His gratitude for the imperial kindness and his reverence for the imperial virtue exceed those of Boyu ten-thousand fold. The celestial rescript merely shines forth, yet it illuminates the distant lands with its rays; and the people of those lands, virtuous in heart, turn their humanity ever toward heaven.

    Moreover, our remote domain spans more than twenty thousand miles, yet has sent tributes for scarcely three hundred years. Your Majesty has permitted us to observe the rituals of filial service and to continue the traditions of submission. Each time we receive imperial edicts, we are guided by righteous principles. Our ancestors have long revered these, and their descendants shall forever honor them without ceasing. During the Kaiyuan era, when the throne brought peace and the seas were calm, the imperial words were frequently sent forth, spreading the grace of civilized virtue. Our ancestors—the illustrious Heungguang and Heonjung—were repeatedly honored with imperial calligraphy in the clerical script, their brushstrokes soaring like dragons and flying phoenixes, their papers radiant with celestial light, their sacred writing remaining forever moist with divine inspiration. Though we have heard of precious jade being divided among the western kingdoms, we have never before witnessed imperial silver-hook script reaching even to barbarous lands.

    The rescript declares: "How could we compare you to the states of Lu and Wei? Surely you are not to be classed merely as tributary peoples." And in the Dali era, the imperial word proclaimed: "Though you dwell beyond the Nine Provinces, you are worthy to be compared with the feudal lords; among all nations, you are truly gentlemen." This is the affection that forgets fault through love; it is praise that exceeds what a small nation can bear.

    Your servant reflects that His Imperial Majesty, of sacred literary virtue and enlightened wisdom, of brilliant martial might and profound filial piety, following the succession of sages, illuminates all regions beneath heaven. Drawing upon the classic texts and exhortations, he awakens the barbarous peoples to righteousness. Soon all nations shall be united as one family. Yet what grieves and pains your servant is that his late elder brother, unable to receive these imperial words before his passing, lived drinking in the civilizing influence and has now departed bearing the sorrow of unrepaid kindness. The exhortations Your Majesty has granted, your servant has respectfully sealed in jade caskets and placed in golden cases, entrusting them to his nephew Yo to preserve as national treasures. Yo shall inscribe them upon his seat and preserve them faithfully, that when he enters into office, he may encourage the three ministers, and when he goes forth, he may nurture the common people, accomplishing works of virtue and contributing to the harmony of the age.

    Your servant now watches as spring departs and the sacred branches scatter; the distant road is blocked by heaven's distance. His spirit flies like an eagle crossing the seas; his eyes strain like a crane ascending through clouds. Yet unable to rush to the capital to offer formal gratitude at the imperial court, he remains sorrowful.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The references to Lelang and Jinhan relate to ancient territorial divisions on the Korean peninsula, representing Choe Chi-won's learned historical consciousness.
  - key: ''
    value: The "pearl of the pearl-fisher of Hepu" (合浦珠) and the "sword of Yanjin" (延津劒) are classical allusions to transformation and return to one's native place.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Kaiyuan era" (開元) refers to the prosperous reign of Tang Xuanzong (712-755 CE).
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to beating one's thigh in joy (拊髀) expresses exuberant celebration of military victories.
  - key: ''
    value: The memorial skillfully weaves Buddhist and Daoist imagery (immortals in jars, mountains of immortals, celestial pearls) with Confucian ritual propriety and classical Chinese literary allusions to express Korea's tributary relationship with Tang while maintaining cultural dignity.
